 derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Eyre was born in 1318, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert le Eyre, was 48 and his mother, Antionette Fouche, was 48. He married Joan De Padley. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1385, in his hometown, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1318–1385":"1318–1385","1315–1363":"1315–1363","1320–1363":"1320–1363","1323–Female":"1323–Surnud","1348–1410":"1348–1410","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1270–1336":"1270–1336","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1323":"1323","1410":"1410","1320":"1320","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1363":"1363","1270":"1270","1318":"1318","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hope, Derbyshire, England":"Hope, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1318–1385":"1318–1385","1315–1363":"1315–1363","1320–1363":"1320–1363","1323–Female":"1323–Kuollut","1348–1410":"1348–1410","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1352–Female":"1352–Kuollut","1270–1336":"1270–1336","1270–1320":"1270–1320","134